 
 Middletown Rancheria
Of 
Pomo Indians
Of 
California 
 

CONSTITUTION

CONSTITUTION OF 
THE MIDDLETOWN RANCHERIA OF POMO INDIANS OF CALIFORNIA

PREAMBLE


We, the members of the Middletown Rancheria, as established by Secretarial Order dated 
July 30, 1910, as an exercise of our sovereign power, in order to organize for our common good, 
to govern ourselves pursuant to our own laws, to preserve and protect our common and natural 
resources, to provide for the welfare and prosperity of our people, hereby adopt this Constitution.
 
 

ARTICLE I - TERRITORY

 
 The territory of the Tribe shall encompass all lands, historical, current and hereinafter, 

owned by or reserved for the Tribe, held in trust for the Tribe and/or held in trust for any member 
of the Tribe by the United States.
 
 

ARTICLE II - MEMBERSHIP

 
 Sec. 1 - Eligibility for Membership

An individual is eligible for membership in the Tribe, if

A. 
B. 

C. 

Their name appears on the official base roll dated June 3, 1935, as corrected; or
They are a lineal descendant of a person whose name appears on the base roll
dated June 3, 1935, as corrected, or
Their name appears on the 1998 voters list and lineal descendants thereof.

Sec. 2 - Membership Procedure and Enrollment Ordinance

A. 

B. 

C. 

Membership. The membership of the Middletown Rancheria shall consist of all 
persons who meet the criteria of Section 1(A), 1 (B) or 1 (C) above, who are not 
currently enrolled as members of another federally recognized tribe or band, and 
whose application for enrollment has been accepted in accordance with the rules 
promulgated in the Enrollment Ordinance.
Enrollment Ordinance. Within six (6) months of the Tribal Council’s first 
election to office under this Constitution, the General Council shall enact an 
Enrollment Ordinance establishing procedures for processing membership 
applications. The Enrollment Ordinance shall contain fair and reasonable 
enrollment procedures, including the right to appeal and provisions for keeping 
the roll current.
Revocation of Membership. Membership may be revoked pursuant to procedures

set forth in the Enrollment Ordinance.

Sec. 3. - Dual Membership Prohibition.

Any member of the Tribe who applies for and is accepted as a member of another 

federally recognized Tribe or band shall be subject to disenrollment in accordance with the 
Enrollment Ordinance.

Sec. 4 - Membership Rights of Children Who Have Been Adopted.

Any child who is less than 18 years of age, who does not meet the membership criteria 

but has been adopted by a tribal member may participate in tribal youth activities.
 
 

ARTICLE III - CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS

 
 Sec. 1 - Indian Civil Rights Act of 1968, 25 U.S.C. 1301 - 1303

The Indian Civil Rights Act of 1968 (ICRA) was passed by Congress and applies to tribal 
governments in an effort to protect certain minimum civil liberties. The rights guaranteed in the 
ICRA apply in general to all persons rather than tribal members. This Constitution guarantees 
these and other enumerated rights. Habeas Corpus is a term used in the ICRA, 1303, which 
describes a legal request made to a federal court by a person detained by the tribe. A Writ of 
Habeas Corpus generally asks the federal court to review the legality of the detention. The ICRA 
as it appears at the time that this Constitution was adopted is as follows:

INDIAN CIVIL RIGHTS ACT OF 1968 - 25 U.S.C. 1301 - 1303

130J. Definitions 

For purposes of this subchapter, the term:

1. 

2. 

"Indian tribe" means any tribe, band, or other group of Indians subject to the 
jurisdiction of the United States and recognized as possessing powers of self
government.

"powers of self-government" means and includes all governmental powers 
possessed by an Indian tribe, executive, legislative, and judicial, and all offices, 
bodies, and tribunals by and through which they are executed, including courts of 
Indian offenses; and means the inherent power of Indian tribes, hereby recognized 
and affirmed, to exercise criminal jurisdiction over all Indians;

3. 

"Indian court" means any Indian tribal court or court of Indian offense and;

4.  "Indian" means any person who would be subject to the jurisdiction of the United 
States as an Indian under section 1153, title 18, United States Code, if that person 

were to commit an offense listed in that section in Indian country to which that 
section applies."

1302. Constitutional Rights No Indian tribe in exercising powers of self-government shall:

1. 

2. 

3. 

4. 

5. 

6. 

7. 

8. 

make or enforce any law prohibiting the free exercise of religion, or abridging the 
freedom of speech, or of the press, or the right of the people peaceably to 
assemble and to petition for a redress of grievances;

violate the right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and 
effects against unreasonable search and seizures, nor issue warrants, but upon 
probable cause, supported by oath or affirmation, and particularly describing the 
place to be searched and the person or thing to be seized;

subject any person for the same offense to be twice put in jeopardy;

compel any person in any criminal case to be a witness against himself;

take any property for a public use without just compensation;

deny to any person in a criminal proceeding the right to a speedy and public trial,
to be informed of the nature and cause of the accusation, to be confronted with the 
witnesses against him, to have compulsory process for obtaining witnesses in his 
favor, and at his own expense to have the assistance of counsel for his defense;

require excessive bail, impose excessive fines, inflict cruel and unusual 
punishments, and in no event impose for conviction of any one offense any 
penalty or punishment greater than imprisonment for a term of one year or a fine 
of $5,000 or both;

deny to any person within its jurisdiction the equal protection of its laws or 
deprive any person of liberty or property without due process of law;

9. 

pass any bill of attainder or ex post facto law; or

10. 

deny to any person accused of an offense punishable by imprisonment the right,
upon request, to a trial by jury of not less than six persons.

1303.  Habeas corpus

The privilege of the writ of habeas corpus shall be available to any person, in a court of 
the United States, to test the legality of his detention by order of an Indian tribe.

Sec. 2 - Other Enumerated Rights

Each enrolled member of the Middletown Rancheria shall have the following additional 

rights:

A. 

B. 

To participate in its governmental and other activities in accordance with 
eligibility requirements set forth by the Tribal Enrollment Ordinance; and,
To exercise traditional rights and privileges of members of the Middletown 
Rancheria not in conflict with this Constitution, tribal laws and ordinances.
 
 

ARTICLE IV - TRIBAL COUNCIL

 
 The governing body of the Middletown Rancheria shall be the Tribal Council. Except as 

expressly reserved in this Constitution, the people of the Middletown Rancheria by this 
Constitution confer upon the Tribal Council, the authority to exercise the sovereign powers of 
the tribe. The General Council retains all rights and authority not reserved to the Tribal Council.

Sec. 1 - Powers Vested in the Tribal Council

A. 

B. 

C. 

D. 

