To create, pursuant to an ordinance, commissions or other organizations which
may exercise specific delegated authority to manage the affairs and enterprises of 
the Tribe;
To establish rules and procedures to regulate all meetings of the Tribal Council,
committees and other regulatory commissions created by ordinance;
To establish a tribal court or other dispute resolution forum;
To create an annual budget for the approval of the General Council, manage any
funds within the exclusive control of the Tribe and to appropriate these funds for 
the benefit of the Tribe and its members, levy taxes and assessments, and borrow 
money for public purposes; and
To take action not inconsistent with this Constitution or Federal law, which shall
be necessary to carry out the sovereign legislative powers of the Tribe.

Sec. 2 - Election of the Tribal Council

The Tribal Council shall consist of five members elected by a vote of the General 
Council in accordance with the Election Procedures and Ordinance. The General Council will 
elect members to serve as Chairperson, Vice-Chairperson, Secretary, Treasurer and Tribal 
Representative.

Sec. 3 - Tribal Powers and Rights Not Limited.

Any rights and powers vested in the Tribe but not expressly referred to in this 
Constitution shall not be diminished, abridged or divested by this Article. The Tribal Council 
may exercise additional powers as conferred upon the Tribe pursuant to agreements or law.
 
 

ARTICLE V - GENERAL COUNCIL

 
 Sec. 1 - Powers and Duties of the General Council

All enrolled members of the Middletown Rancheria who are eighteen (18) years of age or 

older shall constitute the General Council. The General Council shall have the power to:

A. 

B. 

C. 

D. 
E. 

Elect Tribal Council members and approve or disapprove any salary or wages
paid for performance of Tribal Council duties;
Exercise the powers of initiative and referendum pursuant to Sections 3 and 4 of
this Article;
Recall elected tribal officials pursuant to Article XII of the Election Procedures &
Ordinance;
Amend this Constitution in accordance with Article X; and
Make advisory recommendations to the Tribal Council.

Sec. 3 - Initiative Process - Method by which members can propose an ordinance or resolution 
for adoption by the membership

Any member may propose an ordinance or resolution for adoption by a majority vote of 

the membership. To do so, the member must submit an Initiative Petition Form that contains the 
proposed ordinance or resolution as well as signatures from at least thirty percent (30%) of the 
General Council of Middletown Rancheria. Within sixty (60) days of receiving and verifying the 
petition, the Secretary and Chair will submit the proposed ordinance or resolution to a vote of the 
General Council at a regular or special election. The vote of a majority of those actually voting 
at a General Council meeting shall be conclusive and binding upon the Tribal Council.

Sec. 4 - Referendum Process - Method by which members may review any proposed or existing 
ordinance or resolution

A member may request an opportunity to accept or reject proposed or existing ordinances 
or resolutions through the referendum process. To do so, the member must submit a Referendum 
Petition Form that identifies and contains the text of the specific ordinance or resolution to be 
reviewed. The petition must also contain signatures of at least thirty percent (30%) of the 
General Council of the Middletown Rancheria. Within sixty (60) days of receiving and verifying 
the petition, the Secretary and Chair will submit the proposed ordinance or resolution to a vote of 
the General Council at a regular or special election to be held by the Election Board. The vote of 
a majority of those actually voting shall be conclusive and binding upon the Tribal Council.

Sec. 5 - Limitations on General Council Powers

The General Council shall not have the power to take any of the following actions under 

this Article:

A. 
B. 

Reverse, overturn or otherwise influence any judicial action of the Tribal Court;
Take any action which is otherwise in violation of this Constitution

Sec. 6 - Legislative Appeals Committee

The Legislative Appeals Committee shall consist of three members elected by the 
General Council. The Legislative Appeals Committee authority shall include, but is not limited 
to, the power to review and overturn tribal legislative and executive actions for violations of this 
Constitution or Tribal Ordinances. The Tribal Council shall set forth qualifications for serving 
on the Legislative Appeals Committee. During the tenure on the Legislative Appeals 
Committee, a member may be suspended or dismissed by the Tribal Council only for gross 
neglect, confidentiality or constitutional violation, upon due notice and an opportunity for a 
hearing open to tribal members.

ARTICLE VI - TRIBAL COURT/DISPUTE RESOLUTION FORUM

Sec 1 - Judicial Power

The judicial power of the Tribe shall be vested in a Tribal judiciary which shall consist of 

the Tribal Court, a Court of Appeals and other specific courts as the Tribal Council may from 
time to time ordain and establish.

Sec. 2 - Powers of the Tribal Court

A. 

The judicial powers of the Tribe shall extend to all cases and matters in law and
equity arising under this Constitution, the laws and ordinances of or applicable to 
the Tribe including but not limited to:

i. 

ii. 

iii. 

iv. 

v. 

vi. 

vii. 

To adjudicate all civil and criminal matters arising within the jurisdiction 
of the Tribe or to which the Tribe or an enrolled member of the Tribe is a 
party.
To review ordinances and resolutions of the Tribal Council or General 
Council to ensure they are consistent with this Constitution and rule void 
those ordinances and resolutions deemed inconsistent with this 
Constitution.
Hear cases based on ordinances and laws of the Tribe for purpose of 
determining innocence or guilt where trial by jury has been waived.
Assign fines and penalties as allowed for violations of Tribal law, as 
allowed by Tribal and Federal Law.
Grant warrants for search to enforcement officers when just cause is 
shown.
Grant warrants, writs, injunctions and orders not inconsistent with this 
Constitution.
Establish, by general rules, the practice and procedures for all courts of the 
Tribe.

Sec. 3 - Judicial Independence.

To promote the independence of the judiciary, the members of the judiciary shall be 

recruited from tribes, tribal courts or other entities outside the Middletown tribal community. 
The Tribal Judiciary shall be independent from the legislative functions of the tribal government. 
No person exercising legislative powers of the government shall exercise powers properly 
belonging to the judicial branch of government; provided that the Tribal Council reserves the 
power to conduct administrative hearings and/or create committees and/or commissions that 
exercise administrative hearing powers.
 
 

ARTICLE VII - POWERS OF THE TRIBE NOT DIMINISHED

 
 Sec. 1 - Any rights and powers vested in the Tribe but not expressly referred to in this 
Constitution shall not be diminished by this Constitution.
 
 

ARTICLE VIII - ELECTIONS

 
 Sec. l - First Election

Notwithstanding the above provisions, the election of the first Tribal Council under this 

Constitution shall be in accordance with an election ordinance enacted by the Interim Tribal 
Council which is in accordance as much as is feasible with the above provisions, and which is 
made available to the tribal membership no more than sixty (60) days after certification of the 
adoption of this Constitution. The Ordinance shall provide that the election be held no later than 
one- hundred-twenty (120) days after adoption of the Constitution, and may provide that there 
will be no regular, annual election of Tribal Council members thereafter until April of the 
following year.
 
 

ARTICLE IX - SOVEREIGN IMMUNITY

 
 Sec. 1 - Waivers of Sovereign Immunity

The Tribal Council shall not waive or limit the right of the Tribe to be immune from suit 
in any court of competent jurisdiction, except as authorized by tribal ordinance or resolution or in 
furtherance of tribal business enterprises. Except as authorized by tribal ordinance or resolution, 
no provisions of this Constitution shall be construed to waive or limit tribal sovereign immunity.

Sec. 2 - Express Waivers

The governmental right of sovereign immunity protects the resources of the tribe for the 

benefit of the membership. There shall be no implied waivers of tribal sovereign immunity. 
Any waiver of sovereign immunity must be explicit and use the following format: “The 
Middletown Rancheria expressly waives it right to sovereign immunity for [name of specific 
event, time frame and/ maximum dollar amount]. ” Without this specific language, no waiver of 
sovereign immunity may be implied. Only the Tribal Council, in its official capacity, may 
explicitly waive the tribal sovereign immunity of the Middletown Rancheria. A tribal member 
may not waive the sovereign immunity of the tribe.
 
 

ARTICLE X - AMENDMENT

 
 This Constitution may be amended by a majority vote of the qualified voters of the 

Middletown Rancheria voting at an election called for that purpose, provided that at least fifty- 
one percent (51%) of the eligible voters shall vote in favor of the amendment.

The election shall be conducted in accordance with rules and regulations as set forth by 

the Tribe. It shall be the duty of the Tribal Council to authorize an election on any proposed 
amendment at the request of a majority of the General Council.
 
 

ARTICLE XI - SEVERABILITY

 
 If any provision of this Constitution shall, in the future, be declared invalid by a court of 

competent jurisdiction, the invalid provision(s) shall be severed and the remaining provisions 
shall continue in full force and effect. Those provision(s) found to be invalid shall be addressed 
by the General Council and changes adopted in accordance with Article XII of this Constitution.
 
 

ARTICLE XII  - ADOPTION

 
 This Constitution, when adopted by a majority of the qualified voters of the Middletown 
Rancheria who vote in an election called for that purpose, shall be effective from the date of 
approval, provided that at least a majority of eligible voters vote in favor of adoption of the 
Constitution.
 
 

CERTIFICATION

 
 This Constitution was adopted by the General Council of the Middletown Rancheria at an 

election conducted on Saturday, January 8th, 2005 where the General Council voted 35 

For, and 5 Against, with 46 Abstaining and 2 Invalid Ballots to adopt this Constitution.

